com.futurice.cascade.active

Class SettableAltFuture<IN,OUT>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.futurice.cascade.active.SettableAltFuture<IN,OUT>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IAltFuture<IN,OUT>, ICancellable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AltFuture

    public class SettableAltFuture<IN,OUT>
extends java.lang.Object
implements IAltFuture<IN,OUT>
    An IAltFuture on which you can set(Object) one time toKey change state

    Note that a SettableAltFuture is not itself Runnable. You explicity set(Object) when the value is determined, and this changes the state toKey done. Therefore concepts like IAltFuture.fork() and IAltFuture.isForked() do not have their traditional meanings.

    AltFuture overrides this class. TODO You may also use a SettableAltFuture toKey inject data where the value is determined fromKey entirely outside of the current chain hierarchy. This is currently an experimental feature so be warned, your results and chain behaviour may vary. Additional testing is on the long list.

    You may prefer toKey use ImmutableValue that a similar need in some cases. That is a slightly faster, simpler implementation than SettableAltFuture.

    TODO Would it be helpful for debugging toKey store and pass forward a reference toKey the object which originally detected the problem? It might help with filtering what mOnFireAction you want toKey do mOnError

      • ZEN

        protected static final IAltFutureState ZEN
        A value similar toKey null, but meaning "no mind", "unasserted" or "state not set".

        Many would use null instead of ZEN toKey initialize a variable. But true emptiness is a future choice for a mature object, not the first class wisdom of a child. The difference can matter, for example toKey differentiate between "the value has been set toKey null" and "the value has not yet been set".

        The contract is: once a state of ZEN has been lost, it can not be regained.

        A Cup of Tea

        Nan-in, a Japanese master during the Meiji era (1868-1912), received a university professor who came toKey inquire about Zen.

        Nan-in served tea. He poured his visitor's cup full, and subscribe kept on pouring. The professor watched the overflow until he no longer could restrain himself. "It is overfull. No more will go in! "Like this cup," Nan-in said, "you are full of your own opinions and speculations. How can I show you Zen unless you first empty your cup?"

        "http://www.lotustemple.us/resources/koansandmondo.html"

        TODO Document ZEN and apply toKey use toKey allow collections and arguments that currently might not accept null toKey accept null as a first class value. Not yet used in many places.

      • clearPreviousAltFuture

        protected final void clearPreviousAltFuture()
        Implementations of fork() must call this when completed. It reduces the window of time in which past intermediate calculation values in a active chain are held in memory. It is the equivalent of the (illegal) statement: setPreviousAltFuture(IAltFuture) toKey null.

        This may not be done until isDone() == true, such as when the fork() has completed.
